</i></p><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-14_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3"><span style="color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">Adherence to legislation and guidelines is vital in any regulated industry. The terms "mandatory" and "compulsory" frequently appear in policies and procedures, but their specific meanings can influence how organisations implement compliance measures. In this blog, Dr Richard Dune will explore whether "mandatory" is indeed the same as "compulsory" and what this means for businesses aiming to maintain high compliance standards.</span></p></div></div></div></div></div><button type="button" style="visibility:visible" aria-label="Previous" class="pf-slider-prev none hide"></button><button type="button" style="visibility:visible" aria-label="Next" class="pf-slider-next none hide"></button></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-9fa3" data-category="Collection Suggestion" data-name="Tea" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-kYHfwS doYKjf pf-16_ pf-color-scheme-1"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-hAcGzb cVhebe"><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-17_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-ilfuhL ejXpQB pf-18_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-19_ pf-heading-1-h3">Key definitions</h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-bQtKYq czWvgn pf-21_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-22_ pf-text-1"><strong>Mandatory</strong> - Refers to something that is required by law or rules; it is obligatory. For instance, mandatory training courses are those that employees must complete to comply with statutory requirements.</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-24_ pf-text-1"><strong>Compulsory</strong> - Similar to mandatory, compulsory means something that must be done because it is required by law or a rule. In essence, both terms signify an obligation imposed by an authority.


</li></ul><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-26_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Despite their apparent similarities, the context in which these terms are used can lead to different interpretations and applications.





























































</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-28_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-ilfuhL ejXpQB pf-29_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-30_ pf-heading-1-h3">Key facts and statistics
</h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-bQtKYq czWvgn pf-32_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-33_ pf-text-1">According to the Health and Safety Executive (HSE), there were 693,000 injuries at work in Great Britain in 2019/20, underscoring the importance of compliance with health and safety regulations.



</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-35_ pf-text-1">The Care Quality Commission (CQC) requires mandatory training for all staff in regulated activities to ensure they meet the required standards of care.


</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-37_ pf-text-1">A 2020 survey by the Chartered Institute of Personnel and Development (CIPD) found that 80% of organisations provide mandatory training to comply with legal requirements.
</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-39_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-ilfuhL ejXpQB pf-40_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-41_ pf-heading-1-h3">Importance of the subject matter
</h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-43_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Understanding the precise requirements of mandatory and compulsory training is essential for compliance. Failure to adhere to these obligations can result in penalties, legal action, and reputational damage. For instance, non-compliance with mandatory health and safety training can lead to workplace accidents, increasing the risk of legal liabilities.




























































</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-45_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-ilfuhL ejXpQB pf-46_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-47_ pf-heading-1-h3">Recommended best practices for implementation</h3><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-49_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Clear definitions and policies</strong></h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-51_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Organisations should define "mandatory" and "compulsory" within their policies to ensure clarity. This helps employees understand their obligations and the consequences of non-compliance.


























































</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-53_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Comprehensive training programs</strong></h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-55_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Develop and implement comprehensive training programs that cover all mandatory and compulsory requirements. These should be tailored to meet the specific needs of your industry and regulatory body requirements, such as HSE, CQC, or Ofsted.



























































</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-57_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Regular updates and reviews</strong></h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-59_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Regulatory requirements can change, so it’s crucial to review and update your training programs and policies regularly. For the latest guidelines, use reliable sources such as the Health and Safety Executive (HSE) and the Care Quality Commission (CQC).


























































</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-61_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Utilise compliance management software</strong></h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-63_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Employing compliance management software like ComplyPlus™ can streamline the management of training programs, ensuring that all mandatory and compulsory requirements are met. ComplyPlus™ offers a robust training and development platform, a central repository for compliance documents, and streamlined policy and procedure creation.




























































</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-65_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-ilfuhL ejXpQB pf-66_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-67_ pf-heading-1-h3">Understanding the nuances</h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-69_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">While mandatory and compulsory training are often seen as synonymous, there are subtle differences in their application. For example, in the healthcare sector, mandatory training might include basic life support and infection control, which are required by the CQC. Compulsory training could refer to additional modules specific employers require to enhance skills beyond the basic statutory requirements.




























































</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-71_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-ilfuhL ejXpQB pf-72_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-73_ pf-heading-1-h3">Legal and regulatory frameworks</h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-75_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Different regulatory bodies use these terms differently. The HSE focuses on mandatory health and safety training, while the CQC emphasises the importance of mandatory training in ensuring quality care. Understanding the specific language these bodies use helps develop appropriate training programs.





























































